data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider already blocked sync I/O by default but offered a **sync-over-async opt-in** (via `ConfigureWarnings` to ignore `CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported`). In .NET 11 / EF Core 11, **that opt-in is removed entirely**. All four of your sync calls will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime with no workaround.

## What to change

Convert to async throughout:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`, `First()` → `FirstAsync()`, `Count()` → `CountAsync()`, `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- Callers must also become `async` — this will ripple up through controllers/handlers
- `Add()` stays synchronous (it's an in-memory tracking call, not I/O)
- Remove the old `CosmosEventId.SyncNotSupported` warning suppression from your `DbContext` configuration — it no longer exists
